results.notes:
Growing on sticks next to a well-rotted hardwood log. Caps lacking appendiculate veil remnants. Stems not annulate. Caps and stems drying hay-brown. Pileipellis composed of hyaline, rounded elements. Pleurocystidia fusiform to narrowly cylindrical and lacking refractive contents in Melzer’s. Pleurocystidia measurements: (38) 43.7 – 54.2 (59.4) × (7.9) 8.1 – 9.6 (10.6) µm, Q = (4.6) 4.8 – 6.2 (6.3); N = 10, Me = 49.5 × 9 µm; Qe = 5.5. Cheilocystidia very variable in shape: sphaeropendunculate, globose, utriform or lageniform. Cheilocystidia measurements: (19.4) 20.1 – 35.3 (38.4) × (6.1) 8 – 12.8 (15.6) µm, Q = (1.4) 2.1 – 4.1 (4.9); N = 18, Me = 27.3 × 9.8 µm; Qe = 2.9. Spores smooth, chocolate brown in 1M KOH, and lacking a distinct apical pore. Spore measurements: (6.5) 7.1 – 8.3 (8.6) × (3.7) 4 – 4.7 (5.2) µm, Q = (1.5) 1.6 – 1.9 (2.1); N = 30, Me = 7.7 × 4.3 µm; Qe = 1.8

I visited a field where I have picked confirmed Semilanceata only a month ago. There were many more species of mushrooms out today, and out of my collection, there are a few I worry may be something else. Others had less or almost no nipple, and I could not be sure if there is a pellicle as they were drier. Additionally, I found two immature mushrooms that did not have any veil or partial veil, which I know is a common feature. All stems are shreddable and pliable. I am still trying to get a good spore print, but can see clearly black/dark spores on the older ones.

While I’m sure about a few of these, I’m not perfectly confident about the others, as I’m not familiar with all the possible look a likes out there.

Comment: Cosmopolitan species Blastenia ferruginea is tiny but beautifully colored when wet (as many other members of Caloplaca genus). The species is traditionally known under its name Caloplaca ferruginea, but according to Index Fungorum its current name is Blastenia ferruginea. At first I thought the find belongs to genus Ramboldia (eventually Ramboldia russula), but spores are typically polarilocular, which is characteristic for genus Caloplaca and allied. The lichen was found on the branches of the same bush as Teloschistes chrysophthalmus (L.) Th. Fr. Blastenia ferruginea seems to be a rare species. Smith et al. (2009) (Ref.:1) states that it is scarce and decreasing and has now (2009) probably disappeared from Central Europe. It is not yet listed in the Boletus Informaticus and Mycotheca of the Forestry institute of Slovenia although some records for my country are listed in Ref.6.
